Citations
Date:  0/0/1941
Source:  NZ Slang
Author:  BAKER
Vol / Page:  53
Edition:
Quote:  <i>To bounce the ball</i>, to test public feeling on a matter, to try the market (a phrase popularised, I understand, by a well-known New Zealand politician [the Hon R. Semple] who also introduced this country to the term <i>snivelling snufflebuster</i>)
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1949
Source:  Dictionary of Slang Addenda
Author:  PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page:  998
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Bounce the ball</i>. To test public opinion or sentiment; test the stock market: NZ political coll: since ca1920. B1941. Ex the preliminaries usual among footballers. [i.e. Aust. Rules]
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1988
Source:  Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author:  McGILL
Vol / Page:  19
Edition:
Quote:  <i>bounce the ball</i> political test of public opinion; eg `D'ya think Douglas is bouncing the ball again with all these rumours of a GST rise?'
